      "content": "The phrase \"irreparable harm\" is indeed standard legal terminology used to describe damage that monetary compensation can't adequately fix. In the contract, it means that if you disclose confidential information, the damages are severe enough that the affected party may loss more than just money, perhaps affecting their reputation or competitive edge. It doesn't intend to trap anyone but reminds you of the seriousness of not sharing confidential information. Be sure that you understand what specific types of harm they are referring to and what might trigger those consequences. If this part of the contract feels ambiguous or overly broad, point it out to your attorney for clarification, as doing so will help you to avoid unintentional breaches.",
